 1180":"circa 1180","ABT 1182":"circa 1182","1218":"1218","Büdingen, Oberwesterwaldkreis, Hessen-Nassau, Freistaat Preußen, Deutschland":"Büdingen, Oberwesterwaldkreis, Hessen-Nassau, Preußen, Duitsland","of,Morle,Hessen-Nassau,Prussia":"Hessen-Nassau, Preußen, Duitsland","Kleberg Deutschland":"Duitsland"},"en":{"1164–11 AUG 1194":"1164–11 August 1194","1164–1194":"1164–1194","1168–1236":"1168–1236","1180–1196":"1180–1196","1182–1218":"1182–1218","1190–1220":"1190–1220","1122–1175":"1122–1175","1133–Female":"1133–Deceased","1190":"1190","about 1190":"1190","1220":"1220","1164":"1164","1175":"1175","11 AUG 1194":"11 August 1194","1196":"1196","1194":"1194","1182":"1182","1180":"1180","1236":"1236","UM 1151":"about 1151","1168":"1168","1133":"1133","1122":"1122","27 Mai 1175":"27 May 1175","UM 1148":"about 1148","ABT 1180":"about 1180","ABT 1182":"about 1182","1218":"1218","Büdingen, Oberwesterwaldkreis, Hessen-Nassau, Freistaat Preußen, Deutschland":"Büdingen, Oberwesterwaldkreis, Hesse-Nassau, Prussia, Germany","of,Morle,Hessen-Nassau,Prussia":"Hesse-Nassau, Prussia, Germany","Kleberg Deutschland":"Germany","nameMeanings":[{"name":"von","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Altered form of Welsh   Vaughan  .","Chinese: variant of   Wong  .","Cambodian: written វ៉ុន, unexplained."],"variants":[{"name":"Vaughan","meanings":["Welsh: from <i>fychan</i>, a lenited form of <i>bychan</i>, a diminutive of <i>bach</i> ‘little’. This was often used to distinguish the younger of two bearers of the same personal name, typically the son of a father with the same name."]}]},{"name":"Büdingen,","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Jean-Paul.","German (<b>Büdinger</b>): habitational name for someone from any of several places called Büdingen, in Hesse and Saarland, so named with the personal name <i>Bodo</i> (see   Bode  ) + the suffix <i>-inge(n)</i> which denotes belonging, i.e. ‘the people or followers of a man called Bodo’. Compare   Bedinger   and   Bittinger  .","French (mainly Lorraine): of German origin (see 1 above). Compare   Biediger  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Bode","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Erwin, Otto, Gerd, Gerhard, Helmut, Armin, Dieter, Erna, Ewald, Friedhelm, Fritz, Gunter.","Dutch and German: occupational name for a messenger or representative, Dutch <i>bode</i>, Middle Low German <i>bode</i>. A <i>bode</i> was a medieval official with a variety of different functions.","German and Danish: from the North German personal name <i>Bodo</i>, a derivative of Old Saxon <i>bodo</i> ‘messenger, leader’."]},{"name":"Biddinger","meanings":["Americanized form of German <b>Büdinger</b> (see   Budinger  ) or of its variant   Bidinger  ."]},{"name":"Biediger","meanings":["Probably an altered form or a variant of German <b>Büdinger</b> (see   Budinger  ). It originates from France (Alsace and Lorraine), where it is very rare."]},{"name":"Bidinger","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Franz, Kurt, Merwin.","German: variant of <b>Büdinger</b> (see   Budinger  )."]},{"name":"Bedinger","meanings":["Americanized form of German <b>Büdinger</b> (see   Budinger  ).","History: Adam Büdinger was a German-speaking emigrant to PA from Alsace. George Michael Bedinger was born in York County, PA, in 1756, and was an early settler in KY."]}]},{"name":"Siegfried","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["from <i>sige</i> ‘victory’ + <i>frid</i> ‘peace’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"II","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Violet  ,   Vivien  , or   Vivian ."],"variants":[{"name":"Vivien","meanings":["Earlier generally taken as a variant of the boy's name   Vivian  , but now also rarely used for boys. This spelling was quite common in Old French. Its use as a girl's name in the English-speaking world was influenced by  Tennyson's  Merlin and Vivien (  1859 ). This name, from Arthurian legend, may represent an altered form of a Celtic name (perhaps akin to the Irish Gaelic name <i>Béibhinn</i> ‘white lady’, pronounced ‘bee-<b>veen</b>’). The actress  Vivien Leigh  (  1913–67 ) was christened <i>Vivian</i>."]},{"name":"Violet","meanings":["From the name of the flower (Old French <i>violette</i>, Late Latin <i>violetta</i>, a diminutive of <i>viola</i>). This was one of the earliest flower names to become popular in Britain, being used as early as  1700  and becoming well established in the 19th century, although it is now somewhat out of favour."]},{"name":"Vivian","meanings":["Originally a boy's name, from an Old French form of the Latin name <i>Vivianus</i> (probably a derivative of <i>vivus</i> ‘alive’), but now more frequent as a girl's name. The name was borne by a 5th-century bishop of Saintes in western France, remembered for protecting his people during the invasion of the Visigoths."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Siegfried II von Büdingen, Graf von Mörle und Kleeberg was born in 1164, in Büdingen, Oberwesterwaldkreis, Hesse-Nassau, Prussia, Germany, his father, Siegfried I von Peilstein und von Kleeberg, was 43 and his mother, (Mädchen), was 32. He had at least 2 sons and 1 daughter with Euphemia von Staden. He died on 11 August 1194, at the age of 30."},"et":{"1164–11 AUG 1194":"1164–11. august 1194","1164–1194":"1164–1194","1168–1236":"1168–1236","1180–1196":"1180–1196","1182–1218":"1182–1218","1190–1220":"1190–1220","1122–1175":"1122–1175","1133–Female":"1133–Surnud","1190":"1190","about 1190":"1190","1220":"1220","1164":"1164","1175":"1175","11 AUG 1194":"11. august 1194","1196":"1196","1194":"1194","1182":"1182","1180":"1180","1236":"1236","UM 1151":"umbes 1151","1168":"1168","1133":"1133","1122":"1122","27 Mai 1175":"27.